	\section{Introduction: The Tripartite Cost Framework}
	
	The economic evaluation of advanced research resources requires a structured framework to compare the costs associated with Large Language Models (LLMs) and human labor. This challenge stems from the fundamental difference in cost structures: LLMs are defined by fixed hardware investment and variable token consumption, while human participation is governed by labor economics and platform overhead \cite{CPT_Framework}.[1]
	
	A rigorous comparison necessitates normalizing costs to a universal metric: the \textbf{Cost Per Task (CPT)}. This framework divides resources into three distinct cost models, detailed below: Open-Source LLMs (Total Cost of Ownership), Proprietary LLMs (API Tokenomics), and Human Participation (Labor Economics) \cite{CPT_Framework}.[2]
	
	\section{I. Cost Modeling for Open-Source LLMs: Total Cost of Ownership (TCO)}
	
	Self-hosting open-source LLMs requires calculating the Total Cost of Ownership (TCO), which converts fixed and recurring expenditures into a variable cost per unit of output \cite{TCO_Concept, NVIDIA_TCO}.[3, 4] TCO encompasses both Capital Expenditure (CapEx) and Operational Expenditure (OpEx) amortized over the asset's lifespan.
	
	\subsection{General TCO Formula}
	
	The general formula for calculating the Total Cost of Ownership ($\text{TCO}_{\text{Self-Hosted}}$) over $N$ annual periods is defined as the sum of annualized capital and operational costs \cite{TCO_Concept} [5]:
	
	\begin{equation}
		\text{TCO}_{\text{Self-Hosted}} = \sum_{n=1}^{N} \left[ \text{CapEx}_n + \text{OpEx}_n \right]
	\end{equation}
	
	\noindent Where $\text{CapEx}_n$ includes the initial hardware cost (e.g., GPU servers) amortized over a depreciation period (often 4 years), and $\text{OpEx}_n$ includes yearly hosting, power, cooling, and personnel maintenance costs \cite{NVIDIA_TCO}.[6]
	
	\subsection{Normalization to Cost Per Volume Served}
	
	To enable comparison with API models, the yearly TCO must be normalized to a cost-per-volume metric (e.g., Cost Per 1000 Prompts). This calculation is contingent on the hardware's achieved performance, measured in Requests Per Second (RPS) or Tokens Per Hour ($\text{TPH}$) \cite{NVIDIA_TCO}.[6]
	
	\begin{equation}
		\text{Cost Per 1000 Prompts} = \frac{\text{TCO}_{\text{Yearly Server Cost}}}{\text{Total Yearly Requests per Server}} \times 1000
	\end{equation}
	
	\noindent The $\text{Total Yearly Requests per Server}$ is a function of the Optimal RPS adjusted by the system's expected uptime fraction, which reflects the financial viability being directly tied to utilization rates \cite{NVIDIA_TCO}.[6]
	
	\section{II. Cost Modeling for Proprietary LLMs: API Tokenomics}
	
	Proprietary models (e.g., GPT, Claude, Gemini) rely on an asymmetric tokenomics structure where input (prompt) and output (completion) tokens are priced differently \cite{API_Pricing_2025}.[7] The cost is consumption-based, simplifying TCO analysis but introducing sensitivity to prompt design.
	
	\subsection{Cost Per Task for Proprietary LLMs}
	
	The Cost Per Task for Proprietary LLMs ($CPT_{\text{Proprietary}}$) is calculated by separating the expense for the Input Sequence Length (ISL) and the Output Sequence Length (OSL), using the respective prices ($P_{\text{in}}$ and $P_{\text{out}}$) per million tokens \cite{Tokenomics}.[8]
	
	\begin{equation}
		CPT_{\text{Proprietary}} = \frac{(\text{ISL} \times P_{\text{in}} + \text{OSL} \times P_{\text{out}})}{1,000,000} + C_{\text{API Overhead}}
	\end{equation}
	
	\noindent Where $C_{\text{API Overhead}}$ includes amortized costs from failed calls and vendor usage fees \cite{Tokenomics}.[9] The significant price difference between input and output (e.g., up to $5\times$ or $8\times$ depending on the model) makes the OSL a primary cost driver \cite{API_Pricing_2025}.[7]
	
	\section{III. Cost Modeling for Human Participation: Labor Economics}
	
	For tasks requiring subjective interpretation, ethical compliance mandates that the cost calculation for human participation must include not just the gross wage but also mandatory platform overhead and quality control expenses \cite{Ethical_Wages}.[10]
	
	\subsection{Total Cost Per Hour for Human Labor}
	
	The true cost of procuring human labor in a research context is calculated using the ethical gross hourly wage, mandatory platform fees, and quality assurance overhead:
	
	\begin{equation}
		\text{Cost Per Hour}_{\text{Human}} = W_{\text{gross}} \times (1 + F_{\text{platform}}) + C_{\text{QA-overhead}}
	\end{equation}
	
	\noindent Where:
	\begin{itemize}
		\item $W_{\text{gross}}$ is the ethical gross hourly wage (e.g., minimum recommended rate of \$8.00–\$12.00/hour) \cite{Ethical_Wages, Prolific_Fees}.[10, 11]
		\item $F_{\text{platform}}$ is the commission charged by crowdsourcing platforms (e.g., $33.3\%$ for academic use on Prolific or $20-40\%$ on MTurk) \cite{Prolific_Fees, MTurk_Fees}.[11, 12]
		\item $C_{\text{QA-overhead}}$ is the amortized internal labor cost incurred by the research team for quality control, screening, and dropout management \cite{Ethical_Wages}.[10]
	\end{itemize}
	
	\subsection{Normalization to Human Cost Per Task (CPT)}
	
	The human labor rate is converted to $CPT_{\text{Human}}$ by estimating the time required to complete the specific research task:
	
	\begin{equation}
		CPT_{\text{Human}} = (\text{Time Per Task}_{\text{est}} \times W_{\text{gross}}) \times (1 + F_{\text{platform}}) + C_{\text{QA per Task}}
	\end{equation}
	
	\section{IV. The Quality-Adjusted CPT (QCPT)}
	
	Raw CPT must be qualified by a quality metric to be useful for decision-making. The final metric is the Quality-Adjusted CPT (QCPT), which weights the raw cost against the achievable performance (e.g., F1 score or human agreement, such as Krippendorff's $\alpha$) \cite{CPT_Framework}.[2, 13] Research suggests that LLM-generated data can be significantly cheaper (e.g., costing \$840 compared to \$12,800 for human-labeled data in one study) while maintaining a competitive quality gap, justifying the substitution of human labor for tasks with acceptable performance tolerances \cite{Human_vs\_LLM\_Cost}.[14]
	
	